{"id":"2007.01170","submitter":"Mikhail Malykh","authors":"Vladimir Gerdt and Mikhail Malykh and Leonid Sevastianov and Yu Ying","title":"On conservative difference schemes for the many-body problem","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA cs.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A new approach to the construction of difference schemes of any order for the\nmany-body problem that preserves all its algebraic integrals is proposed. We\nintroduced additional variables, namely, distances and reciprocal distances\nbetween bodies, and wrote down a system of differential equations with respect\nto coordinates, velocities, and the additional variables. In this case, the\nsystem lost its Hamiltonian form, but all the classical integrals of motion of\nthe many-body problem under consideration, as well as new integrals describing\nthe relationship between the coordinates of the bodies and the additional\nvariables are described by linear or quadratic polynomials in these new\nvariables. Therefore, any symplectic Runge-Kutta scheme preserves these\nintegrals exactly. The evidence for the proposed approach is given. To\nillustrate the theory, the results of numerical experiments for the three-body\nproblem on a plane are presented with the choice of initial data corresponding\nto the motion of the bodies along a figure of eight (choreographic test).\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 1 Jul 2020 15:40:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-07-03"}
