{"id":"2007.13478","submitter":"Constantin Rasinariu","authors":"Asim Gangopadhyaya and Constantin Rasinariu","title":"Building Confidence in the Dirac $\\delta$-function","comments":"8 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":"European Journal of Physics, Vol. 39, No. 6, 065402, (2018)","doi":"10.1088/1361-6404/aaddcd","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this note we present an example from undergraduate quantum mechanics\ndesigned to highlight the versatility of the Dirac $\\delta$-function. Namely,\nwe compute the expectation value of the Hamiltonian of a free-particle in a\nstate described by a triangular wave function $\\psi(x)$. Since the first\nderivative of $\\psi(x)$ is piecewise constant, and because this Hamiltonian is\nproportional to the second order spatial derivative, students often end up\nfinding the expectation value to be zero --an unphysical answer. This problem\nprovides a pedagogical application of the Dirac $\\delta$-function. By arriving\nat the same result via alternate pathways, this exercise reinforces students'\nconfidence in the Dirac $\\delta$-function and highlights its efficiency and\nelegance.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 1 Jul 2020 04:14:31 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-07-28"}
